Introduction¶

For this dataset investigation, we will be using dataset obtained from The Movie Database (TMDb). The dataset contains information about 10,000 movies from 1960-2015. Also, "budget_adj" and "revenue_adj" are columns representing values that are adjusted to 2010 dollars.

Irrelevant Features Dropped¶

Features listed below that we think are not useful to us are dropped:

'id'
'imbdb_id'
'popularity'
'homepage'
'tagline'
'keywords'
'overview'

'budget' & 'revenue' will also be dropped as 'budget_adj' & 'revenue_adj' are similar features which are adjusted to 2010 Dollars which will provide better consistency for our analysis.

In [4]:
#Drop irrelevant columns
df.drop(columns=['keywords','homepage','overview','tagline','id','imdb_id','popularity','budget','revenue'],inplace=True)

Renaming Columns¶


original_title => title
release_date => date
release_year => year
budget_adj => budget
revenue_adj => revenue
vote_average > vote_avg

This step will make it easier for us conduct our analysis.

Checking the 'date' & 'year' variables

While conducting this analysis, we noticed that the year from the 'date' column do not always match with those in the 'year' column. Let's find out how many are incorrect.

#Check if both the year values from 'date' and 'year' that ARE NOT EQUAL
wrong_year = df['date'].dt.year != df['year']
#Number of entries with the year not match
sum(wrong_year)
Out[14]:

It seems that the last two digits of both the year value are correct. Let's verify this.

In [15]:
#Check if both the last two digits are the same
date_year = df.date.dt.year.astype(str).str[2:4]
year_year = df.year.astype(str).str[2:4]
#Show the number of incorrect match of the last two digits from the two columns.
sum(date_year != year_year)
Out[15]:
0

Now we know that both last two digits from either two columns are perfectly matched, we can fix this. The dates and years tell us when the movies were being released. And since the year 2066, which is the future, can be found from the 'date' column, we will use the year value from the 'year' column to replace those in the 'date' column.

In [16]:
#Extract the first two digit of the year in 'date'
date_first_two = df['date'].dt.year.astype(str).str[:2]

#Show the first two digit of the year in 'year'
year_first_two = df['year'].astype(str).str[:2]

#Replace the first two digit of the year value in the 'date' column if it doesnt match the year.. 
#..with those from the'year' column
century = date_first_two.mask(date_first_two != year_first_two, year_first_two)

#extract the date value without the first two digits of the year
date_val = df['date'].astype(str).str[-8:]

#Update relase_date column
df['date'] = century + date_val

#Convert back to datetime datatype
df['date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['date'])
In [17]:
#Verify that there are no more incorrect century values from 'date' column
sum(df['date'].dt.year != df['year'])
Out[17]:
0

Creation of new 'month' & 'profit' column

In [18]:
#The month in which movies were released are extracted from the 'date' column
df['month'] = df['date'].dt.month

#Profit can be calculated by revenue minus budget
df['profit'] = df['revenue'] - df['budget']
In [19]:
#Setting index by 'date'
df.set_index('date',inplace=True)
df.sort_index(ascending=True,inplace=True)

'runtime','budget', and 'revenue' have minimum values of zero which will distort our analysis and so will be dropping those entries. We could see that there'a big difference in the maximum and minimum number of 'vote_count'. Since the 'vote_average' is based on the ratings given by the number of people in the 'vote_count', using 'vote_average' would be unreliable. However, we will keep them for illustration purposes in our exploration data analysis.

In [21]:

df = df[df['revenue'] != 0]

#Convert units of budget & revenue to Million Dollar Unit
df['budget'] = df['budget']/1e6
df['revenue'] = df['revenue']/1e6
df['profit'] = df['profit']/1e6

Is the movie industry profitable?¶

To help answer this question, we will be plotting both budget and revenue (both adjusted to 2010 dollars) for movies released from 1960 - 2015. In the graph below, the budget plot seems to stay somewhat constant while movies released from 1960 to around 1980 tend to generate higher revenues than years beyond 1980. Could it be that the number of movies released have risen over the years that may have caused this?

In [24]:
#Plotting the yearly means for budget and revenue
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,5))
ax.plot(df.groupby('year')['budget'].mean(),color='r')
ax.plot(df.groupby('year')['revenue'].mean(),color='g');
ax.plot(df.groupby('year')['profit'].mean(),color='orange');
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Million Dollars, $M')
plt.legend(labels=['Budget(2010 Adj. Dollars)','Revenue(2010 Adj. Dollars)','Profit'])
plt.title('Budget & Revenue of Movies Released from 1960-2015 ')

plt.show()

We can see that the number of movies released have increased dramatically during this period. This could be one possible factor that may caused the revenues to drop. Nevertheless, the revenue plot is still greater than the budget plot and hence, the movie industry is still profitable.

What does the genre statistics look like?¶

The top three genres are Drama, Comedy and Action. War, Foreign and Documentary are among the least genres that movies are associated with. It could be that peoples generally dislike war movies and that documentary shows are not as entertaining as compared to action and comedy films.

In [27]:
def splitDataFrameList(genres,target_column,separator):

    def splitListToRows(row,row_accumulator,target_column,separator):
        split_row = row[target_column].split(separator)
        for s in split_row:
            new_row = row.to_dict()
            new_row[target_column] = s
            row_accumulator.append(new_row)
    new_rows = []
    df.apply(splitListToRows,axis=1,args = (new_rows,target_column,separator))
    new_df = pd.DataFrame(new_rows)
    return new_df

By comparing both graphs above, companies that produced more movies tend to generate higher revenues. But this do not tell us whether companies are actually producing good or bad movies. Given that user ratings are unreliable, one way to tell whether a company produces good movies is by finding the ratio of the amount of revenue generated per movie released.

We will be using the top 20 companies by revenue to further analyze their individual ratio of the amount revenue generated per movie release.

In [32]:
com = splitDataFrameList(df,'companies',"|")
com_20 = com.groupby('companies')['revenue'].sum().sort_values(ascending=False).head(20)


ratio_20 = []

for a,b in zip(com_20.index,range(len(com_20))):
    #Production Company Total Revenue / Total Movie Released by Production Company
    ratio = com_20.values[b] / com.loc[com['companies'] == a].count()['companies']    
    ratio_20 = np.append(ratio_20,ratio)
    
ratio_df = pd.DataFrame(data=ratio_20,index=com_20.index)
ratio_df.sort_values(by=0,ascending=True,inplace=True)

#Revenue Generated Per Movie Release Plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,5))
plt.barh(ratio_df.index, ratio_df.iloc[:,0],color='purple')
plt.xlabel('Ratio')
plt.ylabel('Production Companies')
plt.title('Revenue Generated Per Movie Release')
plt.grid(linestyle='--')
plt.show()

Lucasfilm, Pixar Animation Studios and Eon productions are the top three that have the highest amount of revenue generated per title release. This indicate that much more people have watched their films produced by these companies as compared to the rest which further implies that they produced excellent quality films.

Observations & Key Findings¶

The movie industry remains profitable despite lower profit margain in recent years with the increased number of movies being released.

Note: All observations and findings are provisional and not final.(see limitations)¶

Limitations¶

1)In the original data, there are 21 columns and we dropped 11 columns that we think might be irrelevant to the questions that we want to answer. Not only could there be information loss from this, we might miss out on useful insights that might help us better answer our questions.

2)Initially, there are 10866 entries in the dataset. After preprocessing, the number of entries fell to 3805 entries. That is a 65% reduction in the number of entries compared to the original dataset.

3)Vote average feature is unreliable when factored in the number of vote count distribution.

4)There are some overlap production companies that are owned by one company. (eg. Lucasfilm, Pixar, 21st Century Fox are owned by Disney)
